the mesentery","Pericolic fat stranding","Colonic diverticula","Pericolic abscess","Free gas under a hemidiaphragm"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAll these radiological findings are possible. To confirm a diagnosis of diverticulitis rather than just diverticulosis on the CT, it would need the presence of \u003Cstrong\u003Epericolic fat stranding\u003C/strong\u003E. Whilst locules of gas in the root of the mesentery and pericolic fat stranding are relatively common radiological findings in acute diverticulitis and are suggestive of an acute inflammatory process, the history of this patient is very short and such patterns might not be evident at this stage. Likewise, the history is too short for a pericolic abscess. The finding of free gas under the diaphragm would be rather an unusual finding in a patient who appears so well and in minimal discomfort. At this stage in the patient\u0027s illness the only radiological finding may be the colonic diverticula themselves - but the presence of fat stranding would support a clinical diagnosis of acute diverticulitis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pericolic fat stranding is supportive of a diagnosis of an infectious process."],"references":["Janes SEJ, Meagher A, Frizelle FA. Management of diverticulitis. BMJ 2006; 332:271-75."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70695"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1844"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70695","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/70695"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-21T09:19:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-21T09:19:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1844"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86416"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"at